{"title_page": "Zamaana Deewana", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Zamaana Deewana\n| image          = Zamaana_Deewana.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| writer         = [[Robin Bhatt]]<br>Javed Siddiqui\n| producer       = [[G. P. Sippy]]\n| director       = [[Ramesh Sippy]]\n| starring       = [[Shah Rukh Khan]]<br />[[Raveena Tandon]]<br />[[Jeetendra]]<br />[[Shatrughan Sinha]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br>[[Nadeem-Shravan]]<br>'''Score:'''<br>Naresh Sharma\n| cinematography = [[K. K. Mahajan]]\n| editing        = [[M. S. Shinde]]\n| studio         = Sippy Films\n| distributor    = Ramesh Sippy Enterprises<br />[[Eros Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1995|7|28}}\n| runtime        = 180 min.\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INRConvert|4|c}}<ref name=\"boxofficeindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=2954|title=Zamaana Deewana - Movie - Box Office India|website=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{INRConvert|4.67|c}}<ref name=\"boxofficeindia.com\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Zamaana Deewana''''' ({{lang-en|Crazy Times|italic=yes}}) is a [[Bollywood films of 1995|1995]] [[Bollywood]] [[comedy film]], produced by [[G. P. Sippy]] under the Sippy Films banner and [https://rameshsippyentertainment.com/ Ramesh Sippy Entertainment,] and directed by [[Ramesh Sippy]]. It stars [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], [[Raveena Tandon]] in the pivotal roles along with [[Jeetendra]], [[Shatrughan Sinha]] playing their parents, respectively and music composed by [[Nadeem-Shravan]]. The film is recorded as a disaster at the box office.\n\n==Plot==\nSuraj ([[Shatrughan Sinha]]) and Lala ([[Jeetendra]]) were good friends before falling prey to the vicious tricks of Sundar ([[Tinnu Anand]]), so much so that Lala believes his wife is dead and Suraj is to blame for that. They become the greatest of enemies and create chaos in the city by way of gang wars. Asst. Commissioner of Police ([[Prem Chopra]]) has 2 criminal psychologists, KD ([[Anupam Kher]]) and Shalini ([[Kiran Juneja]]) weave a plot to bring Rahul ([[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]]), the lively and spirited son of Suraj, close to Priya ([[Raveena Tandon]]), the ever-so-graceful and elegant daughter of Lala, hoping to bring the two sides together.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] as Rahul Singh\n*[[Raveena Tandon]] as Priya Malhotra\n*[[Jeetendra]] as Madanlal Malhotra\n*[[Shatrughan Sinha]] as Suraj Pratap Singh \n*[[Anupam Kher]] as Kamdev Singh (KD)\n*[[Prem Chopra]] as Asst. Commissioner of Police\n*[[Tinnu Anand]] as Sundar\n*[[Kiran Juneja]] as Shalini Srivastav\n*[[Neelima Azeem]] as Nisha\n*[[Beena Banerjee|Beena]] as Sarita Malhotra\n*[[Aasif Sheikh]] as Bobby\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{| border=\"10\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer(s) !! Lyric(s)\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Zamaana Deewana Ho Gaya\"\n| [[Vinod Rathod]] & [[Alka Yagnik]]\n| [[Sameer (lyricist)|Sameer]]\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Neend Kise Chain Kahan\"\n| [[Kumar Sanu]] & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 3\n| \"For Ever 'N' Ever\"\n| Kumar Sanu & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 4\n| \"O Rabba\"\n| [[Udit Narayan]] & [[Ila Arun]]\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Zamaane Ko Ab Tak Nahi\"\n| [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Soch Liya Maine Aye Mere Dilbar\"\n| [[Vinod Rathod]] & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 7\n| \"For Ever 'N' Ever\" (Sad)\n| Kumar Sanu & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 8\n| \"Rok Sake To Rok\"\n| Vinod Rathod\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 9\n| \"Parody\"\n| [[Alisha Chinai]] & Bali Brahmabhatt\n| Sameer\n|}\n\n==Remake==\nIt was remade in Telugu in 2002 with Mahesh Babu, Prakash Raj, Raghuvaran and Aarthi Agrawaal as ''[[Bobby (2002 film)|Bobby]]'', which was a disaster at the box office.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0115042}}\n{{Ramesh Sippy}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ramesh Sippy]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Nadeem\u2013Shravan]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Hindi films remade in other languages]]\n\n{{1990s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Zamaana Deewana\n| image          = Zamaana_Deewana.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| writer         = [[Robin Bhatt]]<br>Javed Siddiqui\n| producer       = [[G. P. Sippy]]\n| director       = [[Ramesh Sippy]]\n| starring       = [[Shah Rukh Khan]]<br />[[Raveena Tandon]]<br />[[Jeetendra]]<br />[[Shatrughan Sinha]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br>[[Nadeem-Shravan]]<br>'''Score:'''<br>Naresh Sharma\n| cinematography = [[K. K. Mahajan]]\n| editing        = [[M. S. Shinde]]\n| studio         = Sippy Films\n| distributor    = Ramesh Sippy Enterprises<br />[[Eros Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1995|7|28}}\n| runtime        = 180 min.\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INRConvert|4|c}}<ref name=\"boxofficeindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=2954|title=Zamaana Deewana - Movie - Box Office India|website=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = {{INRConvert|4.67|c}}<ref name=\"boxofficeindia.com\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Zamaana Deewana''''' ({{lang-en|Crazy Times|italic=yes}}) is a [[Bollywood films of 1995|1995]] [[Bollywood]] [[comedy film]], produced by [[G. P. Sippy]] under the Sippy Films banner and directed by [[Ramesh Sippy]]. It stars [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]], [[Raveena Tandon]] in the pivotal roles along with [[Jeetendra]], [[Shatrughan Sinha]] playing their parents, respectively and music composed by [[Nadeem-Shravan]]. The film is recorded as a disaster at the box office.\n\n==Plot==\nSuraj ([[Shatrughan Sinha]]) and Lala ([[Jeetendra]]) were good friends before falling prey to the vicious tricks of Sundar ([[Tinnu Anand]]), so much so that Lala believes his wife is dead and Suraj is to blame for that. They become the greatest of enemies and create chaos in the city by way of gang wars. Asst. Commissioner of Police ([[Prem Chopra]]) has 2 criminal psychologists, KD ([[Anupam Kher]]) and Shalini ([[Kiran Juneja]]) weave a plot to bring Rahul ([[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]]), the lively and spirited son of Suraj, close to Priya ([[Raveena Tandon]]), the ever-so-graceful and elegant daughter of Lala, hoping to bring the two sides together.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] as Rahul Singh\n*[[Raveena Tandon]] as Priya Malhotra\n*[[Jeetendra]] as Madanlal Malhotra\n*[[Shatrughan Sinha]] as Suraj Pratap Singh \n*[[Anupam Kher]] as Kamdev Singh (KD)\n*[[Prem Chopra]] as Asst. Commissioner of Police\n*[[Tinnu Anand]] as Sundar\n*[[Kiran Juneja]] as Shalini Srivastav\n*[[Neelima Azeem]] as Nisha\n*[[Beena Banerjee|Beena]] as Sarita Malhotra\n*[[Aasif Sheikh]] as Bobby\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{| border=\"10\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer(s) !! Lyric(s)\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Zamaana Deewana Ho Gaya\"\n| [[Vinod Rathod]] & [[Alka Yagnik]]\n| [[Sameer (lyricist)|Sameer]]\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Neend Kise Chain Kahan\"\n| [[Kumar Sanu]] & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 3\n| \"For Ever 'N' Ever\"\n| Kumar Sanu & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 4\n| \"O Rabba\"\n| [[Udit Narayan]] & [[Ila Arun]]\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Zamaane Ko Ab Tak Nahi\"\n| [[Abhijeet Bhattacharya]] & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Soch Liya Maine Aye Mere Dilbar\"\n| [[Vinod Rathod]] & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 7\n| \"For Ever 'N' Ever\" (Sad)\n| Kumar Sanu & Alka Yagnik\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 8\n| \"Rok Sake To Rok\"\n| Vinod Rathod\n| Sameer\n|-\n| 9\n| \"Parody\"\n| [[Alisha Chinai]] & Bali Brahmabhatt\n| Sameer\n|}\n\n==Remake==\nIt was remade in Telugu in 2002 with Mahesh Babu, Prakash Raj, Raghuvaran and Aarthi Agrawaal as ''[[Bobby (2002 film)|Bobby]]'', which was a disaster at the box office.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0115042}}\n{{Ramesh Sippy}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ramesh Sippy]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Nadeem\u2013Shravan]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Hindi films remade in other languages]]\n\n{{1990s-Hindi-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mujtaba21", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zamaana_Deewana"}
{"title_page": "Ramesh Sippy", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian film director}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ramesh Sippy\n| image = Ramesh Sippy.jpg\n| caption = Sippy in 2012\n| imagesize = \n| birth_name = Ramesh Sipahimalani\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1947|01|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Karachi]], [[Sind Province (1936-55)|Sind]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]])\n| residence = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| occupation = Film director, producer\n| nationality = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| salary =\n| networth = \n| yearsactive= \n| othername = \n| spouse = [[Kiran Juneja]]\n| children = Sheena Sippy, Sonya Sippy, [[Rohan Sippy]]\n| website = \n| parents = [[G. P. Sippy|Gopaldas Parmanand Sippy]]\n}}\n'''Ramesh Sippy''' (born 23 January 1947) is an Indian film director and producer, best known for directing the popular and critically acclaimed film ''[[Sholay]]''. He is a winner of the civilian honour of [[Padma Shri]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web | url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | title=Padma Awards | publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |year=2015 | accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nSippy's father was producer [[G. P. Sippy]]. His son [[Rohan Sippy]] is a film director. His daughter Sheena was once married to [[Shashi Kapoor]]'s son, [[Kunal Kapoor (actor)|Kunal Kapoor]] until they divorced in 2004.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0004431 IMDb profile]</ref> Ramesh Sippy has been married twice; his current wife is actress [[Kiran Juneja]]. In the year 2017, he founded [http://rsace.edu.in/ Ramesh Sippy Academy of Cinema & Entertainment] in Mumbai.\n\nRamesh Sippy is also the Founder and Director or [https://rameshsippyentertainment.com/ Ramesh Sippy Entertainment], production house based in Mumbai.\n\n==Career==\nRamesh Sippy visited the sets of the film ''[[Sazaa (1951 film)|Sazaa]]'', his father's first film, when he was 6 years old. His first film job came at age nine, when he played [[Achala Sachdev]]'s son in the 1953 film ''[[Shahenshah (1953 film)|Shahenshah]]''. He worked in both the production and direction departments in films like ''[[Johar-Mehmood in Goa]]'' and ''[[Mere Sanam]]'', which his father was producing. He worked for 7 years as an assistant before becoming the director of ''[[Andaz (1971 film)|Andaz]]'', in 1971 which starred [[Shammi Kapoor]], [[Hema Malini]] and [[Rajesh Khanna]] in lead roles and was a box office success. His second film ''[[Seeta Aur Geeta]]'' (1972), featuring Hema Malini playing dual roles was highly successful and propelled Malini to superstardom<ref>https://m.rediff.com/%0Amovies/2003/may/28dinesh.htm</ref><ref>{{Harv|Chopra|2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, he directed ''[[Sholay]]'' featuring an ensemble cast including [[Dharmendra]], [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Sanjeev Kumar]] and [[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] in his most iconic role as the dacoit [[Gabbar Singh (character)|Gabbar Singh]]. After a lukewarm start the box office, the film went on to become the biggest blockbuster in [[Bollywood]] film history and won major acclaim. ''Sholay'' still remains one of the most iconic films in Hindi film history and a favourite for Hindi film audiences globally.<ref>http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20150813-sholay-the-star-wars-of-bollywood</ref>\n\nNone of his later films were able to match the success of ''Sholay''.<ref>https://www.khaleejtimes.com/wknd/bollywood/remembering-sholay</ref> While ''Sholay'' was a tribute to the [[Westerns]], his next film ''[[Shaan (film)|Shaan]]'' in 1980 was inspired by the [[James Bond]] films but was only a moderate success.<ref>https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2017/may/16/5833/was-shaan-a-mistake-after-sholay-here-s-what-ramesh-sippy-has-to-say</ref> In 1982, he brought together veteran actor [[Dilip Kumar]] and the reigning superstar [[Amitabh Bachchan]] in ''[[Shakti (1982 film)|Shakti]]''. While the film was only moderately successful, it won the [[Filmfare Best Movie Award]]. In 1985, he directed [[Saagar (1985 film)|Saagar]], which starred [[Rishi Kapoor]], [[Kamal Hassan]] and marked [[Dimple Kapadia]]'s comeback to films after 12 years since her debut film ''[[Bobby (1973 film)|Bobby]]''.\n\nHe directed a successful television serial titled ''[[Buniyaad]]'' which focused on the [[Partition of India]] and aired on Indian television channel [[Doordarshan]] in 1987. The last three films he directed, ''[[Bhrashtachar]]'' (1989), ''[[Akayla]]'' (1991), and ''[[Zamana Deewana]]'' (1995) were box office flops and he has since not directed any film, as of 2015.\n\nHis string of hits with [[Amitabh Bachchan]] made him one of the golden directors who had a special working relationship with the actor ([[Yash Chopra]], [[Prakash Mehra]], [[Manmohan Desai]], and [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]] being the other four). In 2005 he received the [[Filmfare Best Film of 50 Years]] award for his legendary film, ''[[Sholay]]''.\n\nHe has produced films directed by his son [[Rohan Sippy]], such as ''[[Kuch Naa Kaho]]'' (2003), ''[[Bluffmaster]]'' (2005) and ''[[Dum Maaro Dum (film)|Dum Maro Dum]]'' (2011). In 2006 he produced ''[[Taxi No. 9211]]'' which was directed by [[Milan Luthria]]. In 2008 he produced [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]]'s ''The President is Coming'' as well as the [[Akshay Kumar]]-[[Deepika Padukone]] film, ''[[Chandni Chowk to China]]'', directed by [[Nikhil Advani]].\n\nSippy's 1995 film ''Zamana Deewana'' was poorly received by audiences and critics, and led to the director abandoning film-making for almost 20 years.  In 2015, he finished shooting his next film, ''Shimla Mirchi'', a comedy film starring [[Rajkummar Rao]], [[Rakul Preet Singh]], and [[Hema Malini]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/rajkummar-rao-wraps-up-shoot-for-shimla-mirchi-762455|title=Rajkummar Rao Wraps up Shoot For Shimla Mirchi \u2013 NDTV Movies|date=12 May 2015|work=NDTVMovies.com|access-date=27 May 2018}}</ref> The film had difficulty attracting buyers as of July 2018, and has not been released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/280316/ramesh-sippy-s-comeback-film-simla-mirch-starring-hema-malini-has-no-buyers.html|title=Ramesh Sippy's comeback film Shimla Mirchi starring Hema Malini has no buyers|date=28 March 2016|work=deccanchronicle.com/|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n* [[Filmfare Special Award|Filmfare Best Film of 50 Years]] for ''[[Sholay]]'' in 2005<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://starsunfolded.com/ramesh-sippy/|title=Ramesh Sippy Age, Wife, Children, Family, Biography & More \u00bb StarsUnfolded|website=StarsUnfolded|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n* IIFA Award for outstanding contribution to the Indian cinema (Male) in 2012<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Padma Shri]] in 2013<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Filmfare Lifetime Achievement Award]] in 2020.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Director===\n* ''[[Shimla Mirchi (film)|Shimla Mirchi]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Zamana Deewana]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Akayla]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Bhrashtachar]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Buniyaad]]'' (1987) television drama-series\n* ''[[Zameen (film)#Zameen (1987)|Zameen]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Saagar (1985 film)|Saagar]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Shakti (1982 film)|Shakti]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Shaan (film)|Shaan]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Sholay]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Seeta Aur Geeta]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Andaz (1971 film)|Andaz]]'' (1971)\n\n===Producer===\n*''[[Sonali Cable]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Nautanki Saala]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Dum Maaro Dum (film)|Dum Maaro Dum]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Chandni Chowk to China]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Fear (2007 film)|Fear]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Taxi No. 9211]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Bluffmaster!]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Kuch Naa Kaho]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Trishna (1978 film)|Trishna]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Brahmachari (Hindi film)|Brahmachari]]'' (1968)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last=Chopra|first=Anupama|authorlink=Anupama Chopra|title=[[Sholay: The Making of a Classic]]|year=2000|publisher=Penguin Books, India|isbn=0-14-029970-X}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=00802693|name = Ramesh Sippy }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sippy, Ramesh}}\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:People from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in arts]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian film director}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ramesh Sippy\n| image = Ramesh Sippy.jpg\n| caption = Sippy in 2012\n| imagesize = \n| birth_name = Ramesh Sipahimalani\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1947|01|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Karachi]], [[Sind Province (1936-55)|Sind]], [[British Raj|British India]] (present-day [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]])\n| residence = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| occupation = Film director, producer\n| nationality = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| salary =\n| networth = \n| yearsactive= \n| othername = \n| spouse = [[Kiran Juneja]]\n| children = Sheena Sippy, Sonya Sippy, [[Rohan Sippy]]\n| website = \n| parents = [[G. P. Sippy|Gopaldas Parmanand Sippy]]\n}}\n'''Ramesh Sippy''' (born 23 January 1947) is an Indian film director and producer, best known for directing the popular and critically acclaimed film ''[[Sholay]]''. He is a winner of the civilian honour of [[Padma Shri]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web | url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | title=Padma Awards | publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |year=2015 | accessdate=21 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nSippy's father was producer [[G. P. Sippy]]. His son [[Rohan Sippy]] is a film director. His daughter Sheena was once married to [[Shashi Kapoor]]'s son, [[Kunal Kapoor (actor)|Kunal Kapoor]] until they divorced in 2004.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0004431 IMDb profile]</ref> Ramesh Sippy has been married twice; his current wife is actress [[Kiran Juneja]]. In the year 2017, he founded [http://rsace.edu.in/ Ramesh Sippy Academy of Cinema & Entertainment] in Mumbai.\n\n==Career==\nRamesh Sippy visited the sets of the film ''[[Sazaa (1951 film)|Sazaa]]'', his father's first film, when he was 6 years old. His first film job came at age nine, when he played [[Achala Sachdev]]'s son in the 1953 film ''[[Shahenshah (1953 film)|Shahenshah]]''. He worked in both the production and direction departments in films like ''[[Johar-Mehmood in Goa]]'' and ''[[Mere Sanam]]'', which his father was producing. He worked for 7 years as an assistant before becoming the director of ''[[Andaz (1971 film)|Andaz]]'', in 1971 which starred [[Shammi Kapoor]], [[Hema Malini]] and [[Rajesh Khanna]] in lead roles and was a box office success. His second film ''[[Seeta Aur Geeta]]'' (1972), featuring Hema Malini playing dual roles was highly successful and propelled Malini to superstardom<ref>https://m.rediff.com/%0Amovies/2003/may/28dinesh.htm</ref><ref>{{Harv|Chopra|2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, he directed ''[[Sholay]]'' featuring an ensemble cast including [[Dharmendra]], [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Sanjeev Kumar]] and [[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] in his most iconic role as the dacoit [[Gabbar Singh (character)|Gabbar Singh]]. After a lukewarm start the box office, the film went on to become the biggest blockbuster in [[Bollywood]] film history and won major acclaim. ''Sholay'' still remains one of the most iconic films in Hindi film history and a favourite for Hindi film audiences globally.<ref>http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20150813-sholay-the-star-wars-of-bollywood</ref>\n\nNone of his later films were able to match the success of ''Sholay''.<ref>https://www.khaleejtimes.com/wknd/bollywood/remembering-sholay</ref> While ''Sholay'' was a tribute to the [[Westerns]], his next film ''[[Shaan (film)|Shaan]]'' in 1980 was inspired by the [[James Bond]] films but was only a moderate success.<ref>https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2017/may/16/5833/was-shaan-a-mistake-after-sholay-here-s-what-ramesh-sippy-has-to-say</ref> In 1982, he brought together veteran actor [[Dilip Kumar]] and the reigning superstar [[Amitabh Bachchan]] in ''[[Shakti (1982 film)|Shakti]]''. While the film was only moderately successful, it won the [[Filmfare Best Movie Award]]. In 1985, he directed [[Saagar (1985 film)|Saagar]], which starred [[Rishi Kapoor]], [[Kamal Hassan]] and marked [[Dimple Kapadia]]'s comeback to films after 12 years since her debut film ''[[Bobby (1973 film)|Bobby]]''.\n\nHe directed a successful television serial titled ''[[Buniyaad]]'' which focused on the [[Partition of India]] and aired on Indian television channel [[Doordarshan]] in 1987. The last three films he directed, ''[[Bhrashtachar]]'' (1989), ''[[Akayla]]'' (1991), and ''[[Zamana Deewana]]'' (1995) were box office flops and he has since not directed any film, as of 2015.\n\nHis string of hits with [[Amitabh Bachchan]] made him one of the golden directors who had a special working relationship with the actor ([[Yash Chopra]], [[Prakash Mehra]], [[Manmohan Desai]], and [[Hrishikesh Mukherjee]] being the other four). In 2005 he received the [[Filmfare Best Film of 50 Years]] award for his legendary film, ''[[Sholay]]''.\n\nHe has produced films directed by his son [[Rohan Sippy]], such as ''[[Kuch Naa Kaho]]'' (2003), ''[[Bluffmaster]]'' (2005) and ''[[Dum Maaro Dum (film)|Dum Maro Dum]]'' (2011). In 2006 he produced ''[[Taxi No. 9211]]'' which was directed by [[Milan Luthria]]. In 2008 he produced [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]]'s ''The President is Coming'' as well as the [[Akshay Kumar]]-[[Deepika Padukone]] film, ''[[Chandni Chowk to China]]'', directed by [[Nikhil Advani]].\n\nSippy's 1995 film ''Zamana Deewana'' was poorly received by audiences and critics, and led to the director abandoning film-making for almost 20 years.  In 2015, he finished shooting his next film, ''Shimla Mirchi'', a comedy film starring [[Rajkummar Rao]], [[Rakul Preet Singh]], and [[Hema Malini]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/rajkummar-rao-wraps-up-shoot-for-shimla-mirchi-762455|title=Rajkummar Rao Wraps up Shoot For Shimla Mirchi \u2013 NDTV Movies|date=12 May 2015|work=NDTVMovies.com|access-date=27 May 2018}}</ref> The film had difficulty attracting buyers as of July 2018, and has not been released.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/280316/ramesh-sippy-s-comeback-film-simla-mirch-starring-hema-malini-has-no-buyers.html|title=Ramesh Sippy's comeback film Shimla Mirchi starring Hema Malini has no buyers|date=28 March 2016|work=deccanchronicle.com/|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n* [[Filmfare Special Award|Filmfare Best Film of 50 Years]] for ''[[Sholay]]'' in 2005<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://starsunfolded.com/ramesh-sippy/|title=Ramesh Sippy Age, Wife, Children, Family, Biography & More \u00bb StarsUnfolded|website=StarsUnfolded|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n* IIFA Award for outstanding contribution to the Indian cinema (Male) in 2012<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Padma Shri]] in 2013<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Filmfare Lifetime Achievement Award]] in 2020.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Director===\n* ''[[Shimla Mirchi (film)|Shimla Mirchi]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Zamana Deewana]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Akayla]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Bhrashtachar]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Buniyaad]]'' (1987) television drama-series\n* ''[[Zameen (film)#Zameen (1987)|Zameen]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Saagar (1985 film)|Saagar]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Shakti (1982 film)|Shakti]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Shaan (film)|Shaan]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Sholay]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Seeta Aur Geeta]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Andaz (1971 film)|Andaz]]'' (1971)\n\n===Producer===\n*''[[Sonali Cable]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Nautanki Saala]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Dum Maaro Dum (film)|Dum Maaro Dum]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Chandni Chowk to China]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Fear (2007 film)|Fear]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Taxi No. 9211]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Bluffmaster!]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Kuch Naa Kaho]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Trishna (1978 film)|Trishna]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Brahmachari (Hindi film)|Brahmachari]]'' (1968)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last=Chopra|first=Anupama|authorlink=Anupama Chopra|title=[[Sholay: The Making of a Classic]]|year=2000|publisher=Penguin Books, India|isbn=0-14-029970-X}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=00802693|name = Ramesh Sippy }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sippy, Ramesh}}\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:People from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in arts]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "Mujtaba21", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I have added a new sentence and also included an external link to a website for which ramesh sippy is founder and director)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramesh_Sippy"}
{"title_page": "Anna Foerster", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Anna Foerster\n| image                     = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{birth year and age|1971}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2012/film/news/foerster-gives-shakespeare-a-modern-edge-1118049914/|title=Foerster: Gives Shakespeare a modern edge|author=Iain Blair|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place               = Germany\n| occupation                = [[Cinematographer]], [[television director]], [[film director]]\n| years_active              = 1994\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Anna J. Foerster''' (born 1971) is a German-born American film and television cinematographer and director. She is best known for collaborations with director [[Roland Emmerich]], working under different capacities on every film directed by him dating back to ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'' (1996), with the exception of the film ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]'' (2000).\n\n==Career==\nAs a [[second unit]] cinematographer, Foerster worked on the films ''[[Alien Resurrection]]'' (1997), ''[[Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]]'' (2002), ''[[Johnson Family Vacation]]'' (2004), ''[[The Day After Tomorrow]]'' (2004), ''[[\u00c6on Flux (film)|\u00c6on Flux]]'' (2005) and ''[[10,000 BC (film)|10,000 BC]]'' (2008), also working as a [[second unit director]] on the latter four films.<ref name=\"HD Magazine\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.definitionmagazine.com/journal/2011/8/16/renaissance-woman-anna-j-foerster.html|title=Renaissance Woman: Anna J Foerster|journal=HD Magazine|date=August 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe was the cinematographer for the visual effects and/or miniature unit on ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'' (1996), ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' (1998), ''[[Pitch Black (film)|Pitch Black]]'' (2000) and ''[[Stuart Little 2]]'' (2002).<ref name=\"HD Magazine\"/>\n\nAs a director, she directed five episodes of the television series ''[[Criminal Minds]]'', an episode of its spin-off ''[[Criminal Minds: Suspect Behavior]],'' three episodes of ''[[Unforgettable (2011 TV series)|Unforgettable]]'', and four episodes of the Starz series ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]''.<ref name=\"HD Magazine\"/>\n\nFoerster made her feature film directing debut with the action horror film ''[[Underworld: Blood Wars]]'' (2016).\n\n===Future project===\nIn 2008, she was reported to be developing a film ''Secret Hunter'' based on the [[Ranulph Fiennes]] novel ''The Secret Hunters'' (2002).<ref>Mitchell, Wendy (May 19, 2008). [http://www.screendaily.com/anna-j-foerster-to-direct-secret-hunter/4039031.article \"Anna J Foerster to direct Secret Hunter\"]. [[ScreenDaily]].</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[J. J. Abrams|J.J. Abrams]] and his production company [[Bad Robot Productions|Bad Robot]] hired Foerster to direct ''Lou'', a thriller about a mother trying to recover her abducted child.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mashable.com/2016/11/29/jj-abrams-to-produce-lou-anna-foerster-to-direct-for-paramount-bad-robot-exclusive/#d3jeipJwe5q9|title=Exclusive: J.J. Abrams hires 'Outlander' director Anna Foerster for thriller 'Lou'|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|date=Nov 29, 2016|work=Mashable|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography as director==\n* ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]'' (4 episodes, 2014-2015)\n* ''[[Underworld: Blood Wars]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Westworld  (TV series)|Westworld]]'' (2002) (Season 3 episode 5)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.annafoerster.com/index.html}}\n* {{IMDb name|0283816}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foerster, Anna}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American cinematographers]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:German women cinematographers]]\n[[Category:American women cinematographers]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:Women television directors]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Visual effects artists]]\n[[Category:American Society of Cinematographers members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Anna Foerster\n| image                     = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{birth year and age|1971}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2012/film/news/foerster-gives-shakespeare-a-modern-edge-1118049914/|title=Foerster: Gives Shakespeare a modern edge|author=Iain Blair|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 13, 2012|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place               = Germany\n| occupation                = [[Cinematographer]], [[television director]], [[film director]]\n| years_active              = 1994\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Anna J. Foerster''' (born 1971) is a German-born American film and television cinematographer and director. She is best known for collaborations with director [[Roland Emmerich]], working under different capacities on every film directed by him dating back to ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'' (1996), with the exception of the film ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]'' (2000).\n\n==Career==\nAs a [[second unit]] cinematographer, Foerster worked on the films ''[[Alien Resurrection]]'' (1997), ''[[Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]]'' (2002), ''[[Johnson Family Vacation]]'' (2004), ''[[The Day After Tomorrow]]'' (2004), ''[[\u00c6on Flux (film)|\u00c6on Flux]]'' (2005) and ''[[10,000 BC (film)|10,000 BC]]'' (2008), also working as a [[second unit director]] on the latter four films.<ref name=\"HD Magazine\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.definitionmagazine.com/journal/2011/8/16/renaissance-woman-anna-j-foerster.html|title=Renaissance Woman: Anna J Foerster|journal=HD Magazine|date=August 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe was the cinematographer for the visual effects and/or miniature unit on ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'' (1996), ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' (1998), ''[[Pitch Black (film)|Pitch Black]]'' (2000) and ''[[Stuart Little 2]]'' (2002).<ref name=\"HD Magazine\"/>\n\nAs a director, she directed five episodes of the television series ''[[Criminal Minds]]'', an episode of its spin-off ''[[Criminal Minds: Suspect Behavior]],'' three episodes of ''[[Unforgettable (2011 TV series)|Unforgettable]]'', and four episodes of the Starz series ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]''.<ref name=\"HD Magazine\"/>\n\nFoerster made her feature film directing debut with the action horror film ''[[Underworld: Blood Wars]]'' (2016).\n\n===Future project===\nIn 2008, she was reported to be developing a film ''Secret Hunter'' based on the [[Ranulph Fiennes]] novel ''The Secret Hunters'' (2002).<ref>Mitchell, Wendy (May 19, 2008). [http://www.screendaily.com/anna-j-foerster-to-direct-secret-hunter/4039031.article \"Anna J Foerster to direct Secret Hunter\"]. [[ScreenDaily]].</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[J. J. Abrams|J.J. Abrams]] and his production company [[Bad Robot Productions|Bad Robot]] hired Foerster to direct ''Lou'', a thriller about a mother trying to recover her abducted child.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mashable.com/2016/11/29/jj-abrams-to-produce-lou-anna-foerster-to-direct-for-paramount-bad-robot-exclusive/#d3jeipJwe5q9|title=Exclusive: J.J. Abrams hires 'Outlander' director Anna Foerster for thriller 'Lou'|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|date=Nov 29, 2016|work=Mashable|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography as director==\n* ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]'' (4 episodes, 2014-2015)\n* ''[[Underworld: Blood Wars]]'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.annafoerster.com/index.html}}\n* {{IMDb name|0283816}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foerster, Anna}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n