{"title_page": "Abu Nuwas", "text_new": "{{short description|8th century Arabic poet}}\n{{redirect|Nuwas|the 6th-century king|Dhu Nuwas}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Abu Nuwas\n| image         = Abu Nuwas.jpg\n| image_size    = 180px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Abu Nuwas drawn by [[Khalil Gibran]] in 1916.\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s al-\u1e24asan ibn H\u0101n\u012b al-\u1e24akam\u012b\n| birth_date    = {{circa}}{{nbsp}}756\n| birth_place   = [[Ahvaz]], [[Abbasid Caliphate]]\n| death_date    = {{circa}} {{Death year and age|814|756}}\n| death_place   = [[Baghdad]], [[Abbasid Caliphate]]\n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = [[Poet]]\n| language      = \n| nationality   = \n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n'''Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s al-\u1e24asan ibn H\u0101n\u012b al-\u1e24akam\u012b'''{{snd}}variant: '''Al-\u1e24asan ibn H\u0101n\u012b 'Abd al-Awal al-\u1e62ab\u0101\u1e25, Ab\u016b 'Al\u012b''' ({{lang|ar| \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0647\u0627\u0646\u0626 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0628\u0627\u062d \u060c\u0650\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0639\u0644\u064a}}) known as '''Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s al-Salam\u012b''' ({{lang|ar|\u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0646\u0648\u0627\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0645\u064a}}){{sfn|Khallik\u0101n (Ibn)|1972|loc=II|p=546}},  or just '''Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s'''<ref name=\"Gp2\">[[#GA|Garzanti]]</ref> ({{lang|ar|\u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0646\u0648\u0627\u0633}} ''Ab\u016b Nov\u0101s''){{snd}}({{circa}}{{nbsp}}756{{snd}}{{circa}}{{nbsp}}814), was a classical [[Arabic poetry|Arabic]] poet. Born in the city of [[Ahvaz]] in [[Iran|modern-day Iran]] to an [[Arab]] father and a [[Persian people|Persian]] mother, he became a master of all the contemporary genres of Arabic poetry. He also entered the [[folkloric]] tradition, appearing several times in ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]''. He died during the [[Fourth Fitna|civil war]] before [[Al-Ma'mun|al-Ma\u2019m\u016bn]] advanced from [[Khorasan Province|Khur\u0101s\u0101n]] either in 199 or 200 AH (814-816 AD).{{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|pp=352-3}}\n==Early life; his work==\nAbu Nuwas' father, H\u0101n\u012b, whom the poet never knew, was an Arab, a descendant of the [[Jizan Province|Jizani]] tribe [[Banu Hakam]], and a soldier in the army of [[Marwan II]]. His Persian mother, named Jullaban, worked as a weaver. Biographies differ on the date of Abu Nuwas' birth, ranging from 747 to 762. Some sources say he was born at [[Basra]].<ref name=\"Gp2\"/>\n\nIsmail bin Nubakht: \"I never saw a man of more extensive learning than Abu Nuwas, nor one who, with a memory so richly furnished, possessed so few books. After his death we searched his house, and could only find one book-cover containing a quire of paper, in which was a collection of rare expressions and grammatical observations.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XXciAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=F. F. Arbuthnot, ''Arabic Authors: A Manual of Arabian History and Literature,'' W. Heinemann, London (1890), p. 81. ISBN 3847229052 (reprint) |date=2006-12-13 |accessdate=2014-06-20|last1=Arbuthnot |first1=F. F. }}</ref>\n===Early editions of Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s's work ===\nThe earliest anthologies of his poetry and his biography were produced by:<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last= [[Ibn al-Nadim|Nad\u012bm (al-)]]|first= Ab\u016b al-Faraj Mu\u1e25ammad ibn Is\u1e25\u0101q Ab\u016b Ya\u2019q\u016bb al-Warr\u0101q| title=The Fihrist of al-Nadim; a tenth-century survey of Muslim culture|editor-last=[[Bayard Dodge|Dodge]] |editor-first=Bayard |place=New York & London |pages=312-16, 353, 382, 1062|publisher=Columbia Unversity Press|year=1970|volume=I, II}}</ref>\n*[[Al-Fadl ibn Yahya|Ya\u1e25y\u0101 ibn al-Fa\u1e0dl]] and [[Yaqub Ibn as-Sikkit|Ya\u2018q\u016bb ibn al-Sikk\u012bt]] arranged his poetry under ten subject categories, rather than in alphabetical order.  Al-Sikk\u012bt wrote an 800-page commentary.{{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|p=352}}\n*[[Ab\u016b Sa\u2019\u012bd al-Sukkar\u012b]]{{refn|group=n|Ab\u016b Sa\u2019\u012bd al-\u1e24asan ibn al-\u1e24usayn al-Sukkar\u012b (d. 888/ 889), scholar of linguistics, ancient history, genealogy, poetry, geology, zoology and botany.}} edited his poetry with commentary on meaning and strange forms but completed only two thirds in a thousand folios. {{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|pp=173, 353}}<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=[[Gustav Leberecht Fl\u00fcgel|Fl\u00fcgel]]|first=Gustav|title=Die grammatischen Schulen der Araber|editor-last= |editor-first= |place=Leipzig |publisher= Brockhaus|year=1862|page=[https://archive.org/details/diegrammatischen00fluoft/page/89 89]|language=German|isbn=|url= https://archive.org/details/diegrammatischen00fluoft }}</ref>             \n*[[Abu Bakr bin Yahya al-Suli|Ab\u016b Bakr ibn Ya\u1e25y\u0101 aI-\u1e62\u016bl\u012b]] edited his work alphabetically, and corrected some false attributions.\n*\u2018Al\u012b ibn \u1e24amzah al-I\u1e63bah\u0101n\u012b also edited his work alphabetically. {{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|pp=353, 954}}\n*Y\u016bsuf ibn al-D\u0101yah {{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|pp=353, 1129}}\n*Ab\u016b Hiff\u0101n {{refn|group=n|Ab\u016b Hiff\u0101n Abd All\u0101h ibn A\u1e25mad ibn \u1e24arb al-Mihzam\u012b (d. 871), secretary and poet of al-Ba\u1e63rah who lived at Baghd\u0101d.}} {{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|pp=316, 1003}}\n*Ibn al-Washsh\u0101\u2019 Ab\u016b \u1e6cayyib, scholar of Baghd\u0101d{{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|pp=186, 353, 1122}}<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=[[Al-Suyuti|Suy\u016b\u1e6d\u012b (al-)]] |first=Jal\u0101l al-D\u012bn \u2018Abd al-Ra\u1e25m\u0101n| title=Bughyat al-Wu\u02bb\u0101h f\u012b \u1e6cabaq\u0101t al-Lughaw\u012by\u012bn wa-al-Nu\u1e25\u0101h|place= [[Cairo|al-Q\u0101hirah]]|publisher=\u1e6cubi\u02bba bi-m\u1ea1\u1e6dba\u02bbat \u02bb\u012asa al-B\u0101b\u012b al-Halab\u012b|year=1965|volume=1|page=18 (\u00a727)|language=Arabic |isbn=|url= https://archive.org/stream/FP12042/01_12042#page/n18/mode/2up }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=[[Yaqut al-Hamawi|Y\u0101q\u016bt]]|first=Shih\u0101b al-D\u012bn ibn \u2018Abd al-\u1e24amaw\u012b |title=Irsh\u0101d al-Ar\u012bb al\u0101 Ma'rifat al-Ad\u012bb|editor-last=Abb\u0101s|editor-first=Ihsan|place=Beirut|publisher= D\u0101r Gharib al-Isl\u0101m i|year=1993|pages=[https://archive.org/details/waq45344/page/n2302 2303]-2304 (\u00a7953)|language= Arabic|isbn=|url= https://archive.org/details/waq45344}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=[[Yaqut al-Hamawi|Y\u0101q\u016bt]]|first=Shih\u0101b al-D\u012bn ibn \u2018Abd al-\u1e24amaw\u012b |title=Irsh\u0101d al-Ar\u012bb al\u0101 Ma'rifat al-Ad\u012bb|editor-last=[[ David Samuel Margoliouth |Margoliouth]]|editor-first=D. S. |place=Leiden|publisher=Brill|year=1913|volume=VI (7)|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kitbirshadalarib06yqtiuoft/page/277 277]\u2013278| language= Arabic|isbn=|url= https://archive.org/details/kitbirshadalarib06yqtiuoft }}</ref>\n*Ibn \u2018Amm\u0101r{{refn|group=n|Ibn \u2018Amm\u0101r is possibly A\u1e25mad ibn \u2018Ubayd All\u0101h Mu\u1e25ammad ibn \u2018Amm\u0101r al-Thaqaf\u012b (d. 926), Sh\u012b\u2019ah secretary and vizier to many caliphs.}} wrote an epistle about his faults and plagiarisms.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=[[Abu al-Faraj al-Isfahani|I\u1e63bah\u0101n\u012b]]|first= Ab\u016b al-Faraj |title=Kitab al-Agh\u0101n\u012b|place=Leiden |publisher=Brill |year=1888|language=Arabic |volume=IV|page=[https://archive.org/details/kitabalagani01alib/page/157 157]|isbn=|url=  https://archive.org/details/kitabalagani01alib}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=[[Abu al-Faraj al-Isfahani|I\u1e63bah\u0101n\u012b]]|first= Ab\u016b al-Faraj |title=Kitab al-Agh\u0101n\u012b|place=Leiden |publisher=Brill |year=1888|language=Arabic |volume=XVIII|pages=[https://archive.org/details/kitabalagani15alib/page/2 2]\u201329|isbn=|url=https://archive.org/details/kitabalagani15alib }}</ref>\n*Al-Munajjim family: Ab\u016b Man\u1e63\u016br; Ya\u1e25y\u0101 ibn Ab\u012b Man\u1e63\u016br; Mu\u1e25ammad ibn Ya\u1e25y\u0101; \u2018Al\u012b ibn Ya\u1e25y\u0101; Ya\u1e25y\u0101 ibn \u2018Al\u012b; A\u1e25mad ibn Ya\u1e25y\u0101; H\u0101r\u016bn ibn \u2018Al\u012b; \u2018Al\u012b ibn H\u0101r\u016bn; A\u1e25mad ibn \u2018Al\u012b; H\u0101r\u016bn ibn \u2018Al\u012b ibn H\u0101r\u016bn. <ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last= [[Ibn Khallikan|Khallik\u0101n (Ibn)]]|first=A\u1e25mad ibn Mu\u1e25ammad|title= Ibn Khallikan's Biographical Dictionary (tr. Wafay\u0101t al-A'y\u0101n wa-al-Anb\u0101 Abn\u0101' al-Zam\u0101n)|translator-last=[[William McGuckin de Slane|McGuckin de Slane]]|translator-first= William |place=London |publisher= W.H. Allen|year=1868|volume=III|pages=604\u20135|language= English|isbn=|url= https://archive.org/stream/WafayatAl-ayantheObituariesOfEminentMenByIbnKhallikan/Vol3Of4WafayatAl-ayantheObituariesOfEminentMenByIbnKhallikan#page/n607/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last= [[Ibn Khallikan|Khallik\u0101n (Ibn)]]|first=A\u1e25mad ibn Mu\u1e25ammad |title=Wafay\u0101t al-A'y\u0101n wa-Anb\u0101' Abn\u0101' al-Zam\u0101n (The Obituaries of Eminent Men} |place=Beirut|publisher= D\u0101r \u1e62\u0101dar|year=1972|pages=78\u201379|volume=VI|language=Arabic|isbn=|url= https://archive.org/stream/WAQ17074/06_17080#page/n78/mode/2up}} </ref><ref>{{citation|ref=harv|last=[[Al-Tha'alibi|Tha\u2018\u0101lib\u012b (al-)]] |first=\u2018Abd al-M\u0101lik, Ab\u016b Man\u1e63\u016br| title= N\u0101qidan f\u012b Yat\u012bmat al-dahr f\u012b Shu'ar\u0101' Ahl al-A\u1e63r|editor-last= |volume=II|page=283|place=Calcutta|journal= Asiatic Society of Bengal |publisher=Baptist Mission Press|year=1915|language= Arabic|url=}} </ref><ref>{{citation|ref=harv|last=[[Al-Tha'alibi|Tha\u2018\u0101lib\u012b (al-)]] |first=\u2018Abd al-M\u0101lik, Ab\u016b Man\u1e63\u016br| title= N\u0101qidan f\u012b Yat\u012bmat al-dahr f\u012b Shu'ar\u0101' Ahl al-A\u1e63r|editor-last= |volume=III|pages=207\u20138|place=Calcutta|journal= Asiatic Society of Bengal |publisher=Baptist Mission Press|year=1915|language= Arabic|url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=[[Al-Tha'alibi|Tha\u2018\u0101lib\u012b (al-)]]|first=\u2018Abd al-M\u0101lik, Ab\u016b Man\u1e63\u016br|title= Index: Far\u012bdatu'l-'A\u1e63r|editor-last= |editor-first= |place=Damascus |publisher= Al-Ma\u1e6dba\u2019ah al-\u1e24anif\u012byah|year=1885|language= Arabic|isbn=|url=}} </ref>\n*Ab\u016b al-\u1e24asan al-Sumays\u0101\u1e6d\u012b also wrote about his triumph and excellencies. {{sfn|Nad\u012bm (al-)|1970|p=353}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nHe is one of various people credited with inventing the literary form of the ''[[Riddles (Arabic)|mu\u2018amm\u0101]]'' (literally \"blinded\" or \"obscured\"), a riddle which is solved \"by combining the constituent letters of the word or name to be found\";<ref>G. J. H. van Gelder, \"mu\u2018amm\u0101\", in ''Encyclopedia of Arabic Literature'', ed. by Julie Scott Meisami and Paul Starkey, 2 vols (London: Routledge, 1998), II 534.</ref> he was certainly a major exponent of the form.<ref>M. Bencheneb, \"Lu<u>gh</u>z\", in ''The Encyclopaedia of Islam'', new edn, ed. by H. A. R. Gibb and others (Leiden: Brill, 1954-2009), s.v.</ref>\n\nWhile his works were freely in circulation until the early years of the twentieth century, in 1932 the first modern censored edition of his works appeared in Cairo. In January 2001, the [[Ministry of Culture (Egypt)|Egyptian Ministry of Culture]] ordered the burning of some 6,000 copies of books of [[homoerotic]] poetry by Abu Nuwas.<ref>''Al-Hayat'', January 13, 2001</ref><ref>''Middle East Report'', 219 Summer 2001</ref> Any mention of pederasty was omitted from his entry in the Saudi ''[[Global Arabic Encyclopedia]]''.<ref name=\"bearman\">{{cite encyclopedia |first=Peri |last=Bearman |title=Global Arabic Encyclopedia |editor-first=Aptin |editor-last=Khanbaghi |year=2009 |encyclopedia=Encyclopedias about Muslim Civilisations |pages=16\u201317}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, a [[Abu Nuwas (crater)|crater on the planet Mercury]] was named in honor of Abu Nuwas.<ref>[[Abu Nuwas (crater)]]</ref>\n\nA heavily fictionalised Abu Nuwas is the protagonist of the novels ''The Father of Locks'' (Dedalus Books, 2009) and ''The Khalifah's Mirror'' (2012) by Andrew Killeen, in which he is depicted as a spy working for [[Ja'far al-Barmaki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dedalusbooks.com/our-books/reviews.php?id=00000204 |title=The Father of Locks by Andrew Killeen : Our Books :: Dedalus Books, Publishers of Literary Fiction |publisher=Dedalusbooks.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-20}}</ref>\n\nIn the Sudanese novel ''Season of Migration to the North'' (1966) by [[Tayeb Salih]], Abu Nuwas's love poetry is cited extensively by one of the novel's protagonists, the Sudanese Mustafa Sa'eed, as a means of seducing a young English woman in London: \"Does it not please you that the earth is awaking,/ That old virgin wine is there for the taking?\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Season of migration to the north|last=al-\u1e6cayyib.|first=\u1e62\u0101li\u1e25|last2=\u0627\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0628.|first2=\u0635\u0627\u0644\u062d\u060c|publisher=|others=Johnson-Davies, Denys., Lalami, Laila, 1968-|year=2009|isbn=9781590173022|edition=[Rev. ed.]|location=New York|pages=119\u2013120|oclc=236338842}}</ref>\n\n===Baghdad===\n[[Al-Khatib al-Baghdadi]], the author of ''The History of Baghdad'', wrote that Abu Nuwas was buried in Shunizi cemetery in Baghdad.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_CLpmAAAAMAAJ |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_CLpmAAAAMAAJ/page/n410 394] |quote=Abu Nuwas buried cemetery. |title=Ibn Khallikan's biographical dictionary - Internet Archive |publisher=Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland |accessdate=2010-09-12|last1=Khallik\u0101n |first1=Ibn |year=1842 }}</ref>\n\nThe city has several places named for the poet. Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s Street runs along the east bank of the [[Tigris]] that was once the city's showpiece.<ref>{{Britannica|2290|Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s Street}}</ref> Abu Nuwas Park is also located there on the 2.5-kilometer stretch between the Jumhouriya Bridge and a park that extends out to the river in Karada near the [[14th of July Bridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvidshub.net/news/221/walk-park |title=DVIDS - News - A Walk in the Park |publisher=Dvidshub.net |date= |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==Swahili culture==\n\nThe [[Tanzania]]n artist Godfrey Mwampembwa ([[Gado (comics)|Gado]]) created a [[Swahili language|Swahili]] comic book called ''Abunuwasi'' which was published in 1996. It features a trickster figure named Abunuwasi as the protagonist in three stories draw inspiration from East African folklore as well as the fictional Abu Nuwasi of ''One Thousand and One Nights''.<ref name=\"Pilcher\">Pilcher, Tim and Brad Brooks. (Foreword: Dave Gibbons). ''The Essential Guide to World Comics''. ''[[Collins and Brown]]''. 2005. 297.</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Gado (Author) |title=Abunuwasi (Swahili Edition) (9789966960900): Gado: Books |isbn=9966960902 |year=1996 }}</ref>\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n==References==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last= [[Ibn Khallikan|Khallik\u0101n (Ibn)]]|first=A\u1e25mad ibn Mu\u1e25ammad|title= Ibn Khallikan's Biographical Dictionary (tr. Wafay\u0101t al-A'y\u0101n wa-al-Anb\u0101 Abn\u0101' al-Zam\u0101n)|translator-last=[[William McGuckin de Slane|McGuckin de Slane]]|translator-first= William |place=London |publisher= W.H. Allen|year=1843|volume=i|pages=391\u2013395|language= English|isbn=|url= https://archive.org/stream/WafayatAl-ayantheObituariesOfEminentMenByIbnKhallikan/Vol1Of4WafayatAl-ayantheObituariesOfEminentMenByIbnKhallikan#page/n429/mode/2up }}\n\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last= [[Ibn Khallikan|Khallik\u0101n (Ibn)]]|first=A\u1e25mad ibn Mu\u1e25ammad |title=Wafay\u0101t al-A'y\u0101n wa-Anb\u0101' Abn\u0101' al-Zam\u0101n (The Obituaries of Eminent Men} |place=Beirut|publisher= D\u0101r \u1e62\u0101dar|year=1972|pages=95-104 (\u00a7170 )|volume=II|language=Arabic|isbn=|url=https://archive.org/stream/WAQ17074/02_17075#page/n94/mode/2up }}\n\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last= [[Ibn al-Nadim|Nad\u012bm (al)]] |first= Ab\u016b al-Faraj Mu\u1e25ammad ibn Is\u1e25\u0101q Ab\u016b Ya\u2019q\u016bb al-Warr\u0101q| title=The Fihrist of al-Nadim; a tenth-century survey of Muslim culture|editor-last=[[Bayard Dodge|Dodge]]|editor-first=Bayard |place=New York & London |publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1970|volume=i|pages=352\u20133}}\n\n== Editions and translations ==\n* ''D\u012bw\u0101n Ab\u016b Nu\u2019\u0101s, khamriyy\u0101t Ab\u016b Nu\u2019\u0101s'', ed. by \u2018Al\u012b Naj\u012bb \u2018A\u1e6dwi (Beirut 1986)\n* ''O Tribe That Loves Boys''. [[Hakim Bey]] (Entimos Press / Abu Nuwas Society, 1993). With a scholarly biographical essay on Abu Nuwas, largely taken from Ewald Wagner's biographical entry in ''The Encyclopedia of Islam.''\n* ''Carousing with Gazelles, Homoerotic Songs of Old Baghdad''. Seventeen poems by Abu Nuwas translated by Jaafar Abu Tarab.  (iUniverse, Inc., 2005).\n* Jim Colville. ''Poems of Wine and Revelry: The Khamriyyat of Abu Nuwas.'' (Kegan Paul, 2005).\n* ''The Khamriyy\u0101t of Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s: Medieval Bacchic Poetry'', trans. by Fuad Matthew Caswell (Kibworth Beauchamp: Matador, 2015). Trans. from \u2018A\u1e6dwi 1986.\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book\n    | first = Philip F.\n    | last = Kennedy\n    | year = 1997\n    | title = The Wine Song in Classical Arabic Poetry: Abu Nuwas and the Literary Tradition\n    | publisher = [[Open University Press]]\n    | isbn = 0-19-826392-9\n    }}\n*{{cite book\n    | first = Philip F.\n    | last = Kennedy\n    | year = 2005\n    | title = Abu Nuwas: A Genius of Poetry\n    | publisher = OneWorld Press\n    | isbn = 1-85168-360-7\n    }}\n*{{cite book\n    | first = Norris J.\n    | last = Lacy\n    | editor = [[Moshe Lazar]]\n    | year = 1989\n    | title = Poetics of Love in the Middle Ages\n    | chapter = The Care and Feeding of Gazelles \u2013 Medieval Arabic and Hebrew love poetry\n    | publisher = George Mason University Press\n    | pages= 95\u2013118\n    | isbn = 0-913969-25-7\n    }}\n*{{cite book\n    | first = Richard N.\n    | last = Frye\n    | year = \n    | title = The Golden Age of Persia\n    | publisher = \n    | page= 123\n    | isbn = 0-06-492288-X\n    | authorlink = Richard Nelson Frye\n    }}\n*{{cite book\n    | first = Alex\n    | last = Rowell\n    | year = 2017\n    | title = Vintage Humour: The Islamic Wine Poetry of Abu Nawas\n    | publisher = C Hurst & Co\n    | isbn = 978-1849048972\n    }}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first=Dona S. |last=Straley |title=The undergraduate's companion to Arab writers and their web sites |year=2004 |publisher=[[Libraries Unlimited]] |page=30 |isbn=1-59158-118-4 <!--|ISBN=978-1-59158-118-5 -->|ref=GA}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Abu Nuwas}}\n{{Wikiquote|Abu Nuwas}}\n* {{Britannica|2288|Ab\u016b Nuw\u0101s}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010620031029/http://www.sbu.ac.uk/~stafflag/abunuwas.html The Knitting Circle \u2013 Abu Nuwas]\n* [http://www.al-funun.org/al-funun/images/abu_nuwas.html Al-Funu.Org: Abu Nuwas]\n*[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_id=10&categ_id=4&Article_id=5267 Abu Nawas, the Persian Arab] By Tamim al-Barghouti, Tuesday, June 15, 2004{{Clarify|date=April 2009|reason=has thi